Yes.

00:00:01.750 --> 00:00:02.000
Fantastic.

00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Okay.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Hi.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:05.000
I'm Filippo.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:06.000
I do a few things.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:07.870
In my day job, I'm an open source maintainer

00:00:07.890 --> 00:00:07.980
.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
I'm one of the maintainers of the Go Cryptography

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:13.830
Standard Library, and I used to be the lead of the

00:00:13.830 --> 00:00:15.590
Go security team at Google.

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:18.830
And then in 2022, I quit because I had opinions on

00:00:18.830 --> 00:00:22.360
how you could fund open source maintenance, and people said it

00:00:22.370 --> 00:00:24.360
was never going to work, and I'm that kind of

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:24.940
person.

00:00:24.940 --> 00:00:28.200
Anyway, that's a completely different story, and that's

00:00:28.260 --> 00:00:29.650
what Jomis is about now.

00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:33.280
It's a small organization of open source maintainers, but

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:35.600
it's not what we're here talking about.

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:38.480
You might have also heard that I am on the board of

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:41.680
the PLC organization that was just formed.

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:42.680
Woo!

00:00:43.380 --> 00:00:43.680
Exactly.

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:44.680
Yes.

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:47.390
And that is closer to what I'm going to talk to

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:51.650
you about, because I'm going to tell you about transparency

00:00:51.650 --> 00:00:52.280
logs.

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:55.440
Transparency logs are something I am really, really

00:00:55.440 --> 00:01:00.980
into because they meet the moment for providing accountability for the systems

00:01:01.030 --> 00:01:04.520
that we have and that we can make for users.

00:01:04.520 --> 00:01:05.790
But a step back.

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:07.480
What is a transparency log?

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:09.580
A transparency log is a Merkle tree.

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:11.280
Stop me if you've heard this one.

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:13.380
It's a pen-only Merkle tree, too.

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:15.380
It's not a Merkle search tree.

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:19.030
It's just a Merkle tree that keeps growing of entries

00:01:19.170 --> 00:01:19.360
.

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:23.100
And the entries are things that you want to have a list

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:27.580
of visible to everybody and where everybody has the same list of

00:01:27.710 --> 00:01:28.400
things.

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:31.660
That is a very useful primitive because, for example, think

00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:33.400
about package management.

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:37.760
I'm involved in Go and usually how package management works is

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:40.880
that you have a registry and you make an account, you

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:43.150
upload a thing, but that's very centralized.

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:45.160
Go has a completely different thing.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:48.980
It has a decentralized system where the name of the module is

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:52.690
where you fetch it and there's a mechanism for fetching

00:01:52.890 --> 00:01:53.600
that data.

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:55.710
Stop me if you've heard this one.

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:58.800
But the problem with that is that then you have problems like

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:01.170
left pad, you have the problem that if you connect to

00:02:01.180 --> 00:02:04.220
that website, it knows that you connected to it and that

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:06.230
you're using it, which is not great.

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:09.430
You can fix those things with a centralized system because you can

00:02:09.430 --> 00:02:14.440
put something that saves those modules and keeps them available.

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:19.060
So sometimes having a centralized relay, stop me if you've

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:21.440
heard this one, is useful.

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:24.150
However, the problem is that now you need to trust that

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:28.180
centralized party, just like you needed to trust PyPI and

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:28.790
NPM.

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:33.160
Well, that's what we use transparency logs for.

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:36.130
There's a transparency log called the Go Jackson database, which

00:02:36.130 --> 00:02:39.260
is just a long list of every Go module version and its

00:02:39.450 --> 00:02:39.860
hash.

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:44.000
It's append only, everybody sees the same list, and

00:02:44.050 --> 00:02:47.640
a client will only install a Go module if it has a

00:02:47.790 --> 00:02:51.420
cryptographic proof of inclusion in that list.

00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:52.490
This already works.

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:54.980
You are using this if you're developing in Go.

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:57.080
And a lot of people don't know because that's the

00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:59.190
beauty of tlogs, that you can build them on

00:02:59.190 --> 00:03:03.670
top of a centralized experience, and they just work.

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:07.310
Python has tried so many times to get package outers to

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:10.660
sign their thing, and it never works because either people don

00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:12.940
't check the signature, or if people check the signature,

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:15.300
now you're terrified of losing your key, so nobody signs

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:16.720
, and you don't go anywhere.

00:03:16.780 --> 00:03:21.320
In tlogs one day we turn them on.

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:24.260
And that works, and that's what the system database is

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:24.800
.

00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:28.480
This is derived from certificate transparency, which is what Sunlight

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:31.320
was about, and there's links later.

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:38.910
The point of this is that you can use transparency logs to

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:46.400
provide accountability where it's hard to provide decentralized trust.

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:51.060
Instead of saying we're going to make a decentralized system where

00:03:51.060 --> 00:03:54.600
you have to connect to different package outers and there's

00:03:54.790 --> 00:03:58.200
all this problem, we said Google runs a proxy mirror.

00:03:58.200 --> 00:04:01.460
But then we also said that proxy mirror is held honest by

00:04:01.460 --> 00:04:04.470
the checksum database so that if they ever put a fake

00:04:04.490 --> 00:04:07.950
module in there, the outer of that module can notice.

00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:11.990
Because the same list that every client checks inclusion in is the

00:04:12.270 --> 00:04:14.750
same list that you can just sign up, download the whole

00:04:14.750 --> 00:04:16.390
thing, go like, yeah, that's my module.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:19.480
Wait, that's not the module version I developed.

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:21.580
Google, what are you doing?

00:04:21.580 --> 00:04:26.270
And Google is staking its reputation on the system.

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:30.240
To a cryptocurrency crowd, sometimes I describe it as there's

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:35.380
proof of work, proof of stake, and proof of reputation

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:35.840
.

00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:39.100
Tlogs remove all of the crypto economics, remove all

00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:42.230
of the extra work, and instead say, look, are

00:04:42.230 --> 00:04:46.160
you willing to be accountable for the content of this data,

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:47.810
for all this data set?

00:04:47.900 --> 00:04:49.170
If yes, great.

00:04:49.180 --> 00:04:52.810
We will make a system such that if a client trusts something

00:04:53.350 --> 00:04:56.250
, it means it's forever in a public list where it

00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:57.550
can be audited.

00:04:57.560 --> 00:04:59.670
And if you put something wrong in there, you will be

00:04:59.790 --> 00:05:01.140
held accountable for that.

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:04.770
Which in practice would probably mean somebody forks go to change

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:08.870
what the checksum database operator is, because they're crypt

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:12.000
ographic proof that its steward abused that power.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Cool.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:14.580
So that's why I like transparency logs.

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:16.160
I also like ATProto.

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:19.980
So can we build transparency logs for ATProto collections?

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:21.740
What is an example use case?

00:05:21.740 --> 00:05:24.390
For example, if you're making a package manager on top

00:05:24.390 --> 00:05:25.200
of ATProto.

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:29.020
But also if you have any other situation where you would like

00:05:29.300 --> 00:05:32.790
all of your collections to be append only, never change,

00:05:32.930 --> 00:05:34.500
and be auditable forever.

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:37.210
That is not the case for likes and posts.

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:38.280
That's fine.

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:40.930
Like sometimes you want to delete the cringe post from yesterday,

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:43.460
or undo the like that you did while scrolling somebody's profile

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:47.480
without realizing it was not your following feed.

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:48.750
So those are deletable.

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:49.760
Fantastic.

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:52.470
But instead there are other applications where it makes sense to not

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:54.920
want deletions, not want things to change.

00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:58.850
So let's say that you made some full collection and ABC

00:05:59.090 --> 00:06:03.280
collection that you would like as a client to use, knowing

00:06:03.570 --> 00:06:05.710
that those records can't go away.

00:06:05.740 --> 00:06:09.370
Here's a sketch of how that could work in protocol.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:14.180
Alice is developing a client that wants to consume Foo and

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:18.280
ABC records, and she requests for a T log to be

00:06:18.280 --> 00:06:19.240
operated.

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:22.700
So she makes a record called a T log config and says

00:06:22.700 --> 00:06:25.130
, "Hey, here are some collections, some NSID

00:06:25.190 --> 00:06:28.530
s, some DIDs, can somebody please run a T

00:06:28.530 --> 00:06:32.090
log out of these?" And a T log operator, which

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:37.630
can be multiple ones because permissionlessly allows picking different operators,

00:06:37.630 --> 00:06:40.070
like Geomys could say, "Sure, we'll

00:06:40.230 --> 00:06:43.450
run T logs for free up to a million entries in the

00:06:43.450 --> 00:06:46.280
T log." It's going to be what?

00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:48.070
How much can a banana cost?

00:06:48.910 --> 00:06:50.140
200 megabytes?

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:53.040
And it will create a T log, so it will take

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:57.200
all of these records using tap, put them into that append

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:00.990
-only Miracle tree, publish that Miracle tree using

00:07:01.250 --> 00:07:04.560
the C2SP T log specifications, which are already an

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:07.920
ecosystem that the GoCheck XM database uses, that St

00:07:07.920 --> 00:07:10.120
aticCT uses and so on.

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:12.940
And after publishing that, it makes a record saying, "

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:15.780
Yeah, all right, I'm operating an instance for that

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:18.560
T log config." It's the T log instance record,

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:21.030
it has a strong ref to the config, and the URL

00:07:21.030 --> 00:07:22.950
where you can find that T log.

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:26.010
Alice goes like, "Great, okay, I'm going

00:07:26.110 --> 00:07:30.970
to configure my clients to require an inclusion proof, cryptographic

00:07:31.190 --> 00:07:35.230
inclusion proof in this T log before they trust a record."

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:38.720
And this is nice, because even if our tap instance mess

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:42.050
es something up and we lose this record over here, it

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:44.250
doesn't end up in the T log, so it's

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:46.360
as good as if it didn't exist.

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:49.820
Because the client will not accept that record, will not process

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:52.160
it, will not trust it, will not install it if

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:54.290
it's a package, will not show it if it's

00:07:54.290 --> 00:07:57.140
an attestation or a blue note or something like that

00:07:57.140 --> 00:07:59.160
, because it doesn't have an inclusion proof.

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:01.770
So all of the things that get actually consumed by the client

00:08:01.770 --> 00:08:04.240
, you can be sure that they're in that list.

00:08:04.240 --> 00:08:07.720
And then someone else can go and monitor that list.

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:09.400
And if they're the package outer, they can be like

00:08:09.400 --> 00:08:10.740
, "Hey, no, wait, wait, wait.

00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:13.610
My PDFs published something I didn't want to publish,"

00:08:13.610 --> 00:08:15.040
or anything of the sort.

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.300
The leaves of this T log, so the actual things in

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:21.370
the Merkle tree, would be the hash of the did

00:08:21.370 --> 00:08:22.840
, the hash of the NSID.

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:23.840
Why hashes?

00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:26.890
Because you can never change the stuff in here.

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:29.630
And it's really nice not to get user controlled data in

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:32.920
places where you can't delete it.

00:08:33.750 --> 00:08:34.980
Enough said.

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:37.930
And then the R key, which probably would have to be

00:08:37.930 --> 00:08:40.540
a times of ID for the same reason, and the S

00:08:40.770 --> 00:08:41.140
ID.

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:44.620
The records are not actually in there, but you have all

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:47.140
of the cryptographic pointers to the records.

00:08:47.140 --> 00:08:50.620
And if a record ever gets deleted, sure, this collection

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:54.790
becomes unauditable, but the other ones are still standing

00:08:54.790 --> 00:08:59.400
, because you can still check what the full set of those

00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:02.140
were by monitoring the T log.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:05.560
And then I guess we can also put the checkpoint back into

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:08.140
the protocol, because why not?

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:09.140
I mean.

00:09:09.140 --> 00:09:10.200
So, yes.

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:13.460
This is a thing that we can build very easily, because

00:09:13.530 --> 00:09:16.530
T log tooling, we've been developing it now for years

00:09:16.530 --> 00:09:18.960
to make it easy and cheap to run, and there are

00:09:19.030 --> 00:09:21.080
a bunch of libraries now.

00:09:21.140 --> 00:09:25.700
There is deployed software that already uses this, GoCheck some

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:28.860
database, SigSum, SigStore, soon probably

00:09:28.970 --> 00:09:32.110
Merkle 3 certificates, which will probably replace the web P

00:09:32.230 --> 00:09:34.140
KI because quantum computers are coming.

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:35.140
Hmm.

00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:36.140
Different story.

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:37.140
Different talk.

00:09:37.140 --> 00:09:38.140
So, bunch of links.

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:42.640
It's just a loose leaf from leaflet, because this

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:44.140
stuff works.

00:09:44.970 --> 00:09:46.140
Right?

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:47.140
I love it.

00:09:47.140 --> 00:09:49.430
And yeah, you can find a bunch of links, and

00:09:49.580 --> 00:09:50.770
reach out if you...

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:53.360
What I'm looking for next is somebody that has a AT

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:55.800
Proto use case for this, somebody that has a AT

00:09:55.800 --> 00:09:59.630
Proto collection that they would like to be able to say

00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:03.540
the list is universally known, and anybody can audit all of

00:10:03.540 --> 00:10:06.140
the things that a client could ever have trusted.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:07.140
Thank you.
